    "narrative": "Our strongest plays for today\u2019s slate center on **Taylor Ward** (71.46) and **Bryson Stott** (70.73), both of whom capitalize on favorable park factors and soft matchups against right-handed pitching. **Taylor Ward** benefits significantly from the 16% park boost against McCullers Jr., and his spot in the two-hole provides the optimal efficiency for run production. Similarly, **Bryson Stott** finds himself in a prime position against Houser; his 13% platoon bump and 11% skill-based advantage against a middling starter make him an elite start, despite the marginal negative impact of the catcher's pop time on his stolen base potential. **Daulton Varsho** (67.96) and **Yainer Diaz** (69.93) also earn high-confidence designations, as both benefit from double-digit SP skill advantages that elevate their output well into the \"Strong\" category.\n\nThe most difficult decision on today\u2019s board was omitting **Jung Hoo Lee** (39.92) from the active lineup. While his base projection remains respectable, the combination of a daunting matchup against the left-handed Mayza and a lower-order spot in the lineup pushed his efficiency just below our 40.0 \"Zebras\" floor. We are opting to bench him to preserve game caps, prioritizing the aggressive platoon advantages of **Jeremiah Jackson** (65.32) and **Tyler Freeman** (60.93) instead. While **Jeremiah Jackson** is buried in the ninth spot, his efficiency is buoyed by a 19% SP skill boost and the opportunity to exploit a slow delivery from the opposing battery to hunt for the stolen bases we desperately need.\n\nWe must remain vigilant regarding the risks inherent in today's matchups. **Geraldo Perdomo** (44.91) and **Matt Chapman** (48.69) are starts of necessity rather than preference today, as they face the elite arm of Woodruff and the southpaw Mayza, respectively. Both players see their efficiency dragged down by significant SP skill deficits, and **Matt Chapman** specifically suffers from a dynamic platoon disadvantage that restricts his ceiling. With **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** off the schedule today, we are leaning heavily on our middle-order hitters to maintain our 5x5 pace. Ensure monitoring of any late-breaking weather patterns, as the park factors driving our confidence in the Houston/LAA and Phillies/Brewers games could shift rapidly if precipitation emerges.",
